  "description": {
    "en": "Master asyncio.create_task, semaphores for limiting concurrency, async generators, async context managers, and error handling in async code.",
    "ta": "asyncio.create_task, concurrency கட்டுப்படுத்த semaphores, async generators, async context managers ஆகியவற்றில் தேர்ச்சி பெறுங்கள்."
  },
  "xp_reward": 80,
  "story_variants": {
    "en": "## Vaathiyaar's Traffic Controller\n\nVaathiyaar stands at a busy intersection. \"With `gather`, you launch everything at once. But what if you have 1000 API calls and the server only allows 10 at a time? You need a **semaphore** — a traffic controller for your coroutines!\"\n\n### Advanced Async Patterns\n\n| Pattern | Use Case |\n|---------|----------|\n| `create_task()` | Fire-and-forget, monitor later |\n| `Semaphore(n)` | Limit to n concurrent operations |\n| `async for` | Iterate over async generators |\n| `async with` | Async context managers |\n| `wait()` | Wait for first/all with timeouts |\n\n### Tasks vs Gather\n\n```python\n# gather: run and wait for all\nresults = await asyncio.gather(coro1(), coro2())\n\n# create_task: start now, await later\ntask = asyncio.create_task(coro1())\n# ... do other work ...\nresult = await task  # get result when needed\n```\n\n> **Key Concept:** `create_task()` schedules a coroutine to run in the background immediately. Unlike `gather`, you can do other work between creating the task and awaiting its result."
  },
